<section xml:id="section-higher-derivative">
  <title>CLO 14: Higher Derivatives</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-derivatives-iterating">
    <title>Iterating Differentiation</title>
    <p>
      Starting with a differentiable function <m>f(x)</m>, I used the
      derivative to get a whole new function <m>f^\prime(x)</m> which
      measured the slope of the previous function. This solves the
      velocity problem: if <m>p(t)</m> is position of an object, then
      <m>p^\prime(t)</m> is the velocity of the object.
    </p>
    <p>
      I can continue this process. If <m>f^\prime(x)</m> is still a
      differentiable function itself, I can take another derivative to
      get <m>f^{\prime \prime}(x)</m>. This is called the <term>second
      derivative</term>. The process is exactly the same: I use the same
      limit definition and the same differentiation rules to find this
      second derivative. <m>f^{\prime \prime}(t)</m> is Newton's
      notation for the second derivative; the Leibniz notation is
      <m>\frac{d^2 f}{dx^2}</m>. 
    </p>
    <p>
      This process is called <term>iterated differentiatione</term>.
      The result of the process is a <term>higher derivative</term>: a
      second derivative, a third derivative, a ninteenth derivative,
      and so on. The key thing to remember is that there are no new
      rules here at all. The rules for the second derivative are
      exactly the same as for the first derivative. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-higher-derivatives-examples">
    <title>Examples of Higher Derivatives</title>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the higher derivatvies of the sine function.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(x) \amp = \sin x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^\prime(x) \amp = \cos x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime\prime}(x) \amp = -\sin x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{\prime\prime\prime}(x) \amp = -\cos x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              f^{(4)}(x) \amp = \sin x
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
        <p>
          If I take four derivatives, I get back to the original
          function. The same is true for <m>\cos x</m>, but those two
          functions are unique among functions for this property.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Now I'll show what happens with higher derivatives of a
          polynomial.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              f(x) \amp = x^5
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{df}{dx} \amp = 5x^4
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^2f}{dx^2} \amp = 20x^3
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^3f}{dx^3} \amp = 60x^2
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^4f}{dx^4} \amp = 120x
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^5f}{dx^5} \amp = 120
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \frac{d^6f}{dx^6} \amp = 0
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Each differentiation reduces the degree of the polynomial by
          one, until I eventually get to zero. If I take enough
          derivatives of any polynomial, I will eventually reach zero.
          Again, only polynomials have this property. 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-higher-derivative-acceleration">
    <p>
      If <m>p(t)</m> was a position function
      and <m>p^\prime(t)</m> was its velocity (the rate of change of
      position), the <m>p^{\prime \prime}(t)</m> would be the rate of
      change of velocity. That woud be acceleration. Acceleration is
      the second derivative of position.
    </p>
    <p>
      This has important implications for physics. Newton's first law
      of motion, <m>F = ma</m>, says that force equals mass times
      acceleration. If force depends on position (as it often does),
      then I can write Newton's first law as a differential equation.
      <md>
        F(p) = m \frac{d^2 p}{dt^2}
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      As with most of the fundamentals of physics, Newtonian
      motion is determined by the solution of a differential equation.
      But, since acceleration is involved, the differential equation
      for Newton's law needs a second derivative. This is very common
      for physics: most of the fundamental equations in physics, the
      basic model that underpin the discipline at its very core, are
      differential equation with second order derivatives. It's not an
      exageration to say that the major breakthroughs in physics often
      revolve around finding the right differential equations to
      describe a system. 
    </p>
    <p>
      A specific example is Hooke's law. This law describes the
      force caused by a spring; the law states that the force is
      (negatively) proportional to the distance from equalibrium. If
      equalibrium is at <m>p=0</m>, then <m>F = -kp</m>. Using
      Newton's first law with this force produces a differential equation.
      <md>
        -kp = m \frac{d^2 p}{dt^2}
      </md>
      The behaviour of an object on a (perfect, frictionless) spring is
      determined by this differential equation. What is that behaviour?
      I simply have to figure out which function <m>p(t)</m> matches
      this differential equation. In this case, there are two
      solutions.
      <md>
        <mrow>
        p(t) \amp = \sin \left( \sqrt{\frac{m}{k}} t \right) \amp
        \text{or} \amp \amp p(t) \amp= \cos \left( \sqrt{\frac{m}{k}}
        t \right)
        </mrow>
      </md>
      Since the sinusoidal functions solve the differential equation,
      I can conclude that an object on a spring should act with a
      sinusoidal behaviour. Since there is no friction in this system,
      this sinusoidal solution continues for ever. 
    </p>
    <p>
      If I wanted, I could add friction into the system as well. How
      does friction work? Well, friction is a resistance generated by
      movement and movement is measured by velocity. Therefore,
      friction should be somehow proportional to velocity and the
      coefficient should be negative, to indicate that it is acting to
      slow down the system. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Here area is Hooke's law. 
      <md>
        -kp = m \frac{d^2 p}{dt^2}
      </md>
      Then I'll add a term which is a constant multiplied by
      velocity, which is the first derivative. The new constant is
      <m>b</m>, which is called the coefficient of friction.
      <md>
        -kp - b \frac{dp}{dt}  = m \frac{d^2 p}{dt^2}
      </md>
      I'll rearrange this to put is all on one side of the equation,
      which is the conventional way of presenting this equation. 
      <md>
        0 = m \frac{d^2 p}{dt^2} + b \frac{dp}{dt}  + kp 
      </md>
      This is now a differential equation for an opject on a spring
      including friction. We won't at all get into the method for
      solving this, but just stating this equaiton is an
      accomplishment. If you want to check the derivative (it is quite
      a bit of work), feel free: here is the solution under
      the assumption that <m>b^2 \lt 4km</m>. 
      <md>
        <mrow>
        p(t) \amp = e^{-\frac{-b}{2m}t} \sin \left( \frac{\sqrt{4km -
        b^2}}{2n} t \right) \amp
        \text{or} \amp \amp p(t) \amp = e^{-\frac{-b}{2m}t} \cos \left(
        \frac{\sqrt{4km - b^2}}{2m} t \right)
        </mrow>
      </md>
      This is a pretty complicated mess, but it does describe
      oscilating with exponential decay. The friction will cause the
      object on a spring to slow down and the amplitude to decay. In
      the end, it will come to a rest. 
    </p>
    <p>
      This model is called the damped harmonic oscillator. In
      population dynamics, I talked about the Malthusian model and the
      logistic model as fundamental models for many problems; many
      other sophisticated models are extentions and elaborations on
      these basic cases. The same is true here. The dampled harmonic
      oscillator is a fundamental model. It describes, in rough, any
      motion that oscillated with friction and it forms the basis of
      many other extension. It's fundamental. And now, with the
      language of higher derivative, we can state the model and
      understand what the differential equation is trying to
      accomplish.
    </p>
    <p>
      Finally, this is another good example of something I talked
      about ub <xref ref="section-differential-equations"/>.
      Differential equation are particular useful because observations
      about the work often produce information that can be put into a
      differential equation. I can observe mass, the coefficient of
      friction, and the stiffness of a spring. I can watch the motion,
      but I don't directly have a function for the motion. Instead of
      just guessing for the function, I can instead put the
      observations into the differential equation and then solve the
      differential equation. This is how much of applied mathematics
      work: observe the work, take the observations to make a
      differential equation, then try to solve the differential
      equation to actually get the function that describes the
      situation. 
    </p>
  </subsection>
</section>
